/**
 * @page tutorial_ai_behavior Tutorial: AI and Behavior Trees
 *
 * @tableofcontents
 *
 * `common_game_server` ships a lightweight, header-only behavior
 * tree framework for NPC AI. This tutorial walks through the core
 * node types (Sequence, Selector, Parallel, Action, Condition, and
 * the decorator nodes), the per-entity `Blackboard` for sharing
 * data between nodes, the `AIBrain` component that attaches a tree
 * to an ECS entity, and the patrol → aggro → flee pattern that
 * most MMO NPCs use.
 *
 * **Compilable version**: `examples/06_ai_behavior.cpp`
 *
 * @section tut_ai_setup Setup
 *
 * Include the behavior tree header, the AI types, and the
 * `AIBrain` component:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * #include "cgs/game/ai_components.hpp"
 * #include "cgs/game/ai_system.hpp"
 * #include "cgs/game/ai_types.hpp"
 * #include "cgs/game/behavior_tree.hpp"
 *
 * using namespace cgs::game;
 * @endcode
 *
 * Link against `cgs::game_ai_system`.
 *
 * @section tut_ai_mental_model Mental Model
 *
 * A **behavior tree** is an ordered tree of `BTNode` objects. Each
 * tick, the root node is asked for a status (`Success`, `Failure`,
 * or `Running`) and the tree recursively evaluates children. Unlike
 * a finite state machine, a BT does not store "where am I" in the
 * nodes — the tree is stateless at the whole-tree level (individual
 * composite nodes remember which child they were running).
 *
 * Three fundamental composite types:
 *
 * | Type | Rule |
 * |---|---|
 * | **Sequence** | Runs children left-to-right. Succeeds when all succeed. Fails on first failure. Returns Running when a child is Running. |
 * | **Selector** | Runs children left-to-right. Succeeds on first success. Fails when all fail. Returns Running when a child is Running. |
 * | **Parallel** | Ticks all children every call. Policy decides whether `RequireAll` or `RequireOne` triggers Success. |
 *
 * Two leaf types:
 *
 * | Type | Purpose |
 * |---|---|
 * | **Condition** | Wraps a predicate `bool(BTContext&)`. Returns Success/Failure. |
 * | **Action** | Wraps an action `BTStatus(BTContext&)`. Returns any of the three statuses. |
 *
 * Two decorator types (single child):
 *
 * | Type | Purpose |
 * |---|---|
 * | **Inverter** | Flips child Success ↔ Failure |
 * | **Repeater** | Re-runs the child N times (or forever) |
 *
 * @section tut_ai_bt_status BTStatus and the Tick Loop
 *
 * Every node returns `BTStatus`:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * enum class BTStatus : uint8_t {
 *     Success,  // node completed successfully
 *     Failure,  // node failed
 *     Running   // node still in progress (resume next tick)
 * };
 * @endcode
 *
 * `Running` is the "continuation" state — when a child returns
 * Running, its parent returns Running too, and the AI system moves
 * on to other NPCs. The next tick resumes from the same child.
 * This is how long-running actions (e.g., "walk to waypoint") work
 * without blocking the game loop.
 *
 * @section tut_ai_building Building a Tree
 *
 * Trees are built bottom-up with `std::unique_ptr<BTNode>`:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * auto root = std::make_unique<BTSelector>();
 *
 * auto fleeSeq = std::make_unique<BTSequence>();
 * fleeSeq->AddChild(std::make_unique<BTCondition>([](BTContext& ctx) {
 *     const int* hp = ctx.blackboard->Get<int>("health");
 *     return hp != nullptr && *hp < 30;
 * }));
 * fleeSeq->AddChild(std::make_unique<BTAction>([](BTContext& ctx) {
 *     // move away from threat ...
 *     return BTStatus::Success;
 * }));
 *
 * root->AddChild(std::move(fleeSeq));
 * // ... more branches ...
 * @endcode
 *
 * Condition lambdas have signature `bool(BTContext&)`, actions have
 * signature `BTStatus(BTContext&)`. Both receive a `BTContext` with
 * access to the entity handle, `deltaTime`, and the `Blackboard`.
 *
 * @section tut_ai_blackboard The Blackboard
 *
 * A `Blackboard` is a type-erased key-value store (`std::any` under
 * the hood) for sharing state between nodes. Each `AIBrain` has its
 * own blackboard:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * Blackboard bb;
 * bb.Set<int>("health", 85);
 * bb.Set<float>("enemy_distance", 4.2f);
 * bb.Set<std::vector<Vector3>>("waypoints", route);
 *
 * if (int* hp = bb.Get<int>("health")) {
 *     // use *hp
 * }
 * @endcode
 *
 * `Get<T>` returns `nullptr` when:
 * - The key is absent
 * - The key exists but holds a different type
 *
 * Always null-check before dereferencing. Use `Has(key)` for
 * existence-only tests, and `Erase(key)` / `Clear()` to remove.
 *
 * **Common blackboard keys** (by convention, not enforced):
 *
 * | Key | Type | Set by | Read by |
 * |---|---|---|---|
 * | `"health"` | `int` | Combat system callback | Flee condition |
 * | `"target"` | `Entity` | Aggro scan | Attack action |
 * | `"enemy_distance"` | `float` | Targeting tick | Aggro condition |
 * | `"waypoints"` | `std::vector<Vector3>` | Spawn config | Patrol action |
 * | `"waypoint"` | `int` | Patrol action | Patrol action |
 * | `"home_position"` | `Vector3` | AIBrain init | Leash action |
 *
 * @section tut_ai_brain AIBrain Component
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * struct AIBrain {
 *     std::shared_ptr<BTNode> behaviorTree;  // shared across NPCs
 *     Blackboard blackboard;                  // per-entity state
 *     AIState state = AIState::Idle;
 *     float timeSinceLastTick = 0.0f;
 *     float tickInterval = 0.0f;              // 0 = system default
 *     Vector3 homePosition;
 *     Entity target;
 * };
 * @endcode
 *
 * `behaviorTree` is a `shared_ptr` so many NPCs of the same type can
 * share one immutable tree — tree construction is expensive, so
 * build it once at content-load time and point every NPC of that
 * type at the same root. The per-entity state lives in the
 * `Blackboard`.
 *
 * `AIState` is a coarse high-level classification used for logging
 * and debugging: `Idle`, `Patrolling`, `Chasing`, `Attacking`,
 * `Fleeing`, `Dead`. The tree itself is free to ignore it.
 *
 * @section tut_ai_system AISystem and Throttling
 *
 * `AISystem` ticks every NPC's behavior tree, but not on every
 * frame. Each `AIBrain` has a `timeSinceLastTick` accumulator and
 * a `tickInterval`. The system only calls `Tick` when the
 * accumulator exceeds the interval. Default is
 * `kDefaultAITickInterval = 0.1f` (10 Hz), which is more than
 * enough for most NPC logic and cuts AI CPU cost to 1/5 of a
 * full-frequency update.
 *
 * Set a per-entity override for time-critical NPCs:
 *
 * @code{.cpp}
 * auraHolders.Get(boss).tickInterval = 0.02f;  // 50 Hz for the raid boss
 * @endcode
 *
 * @section tut_ai_pattern The Patrol-Aggro-Flee Pattern
 *
 * Most MMO NPCs follow a priority-ordered behavior: flee first if
 * critically injured, attack second if an enemy is close, patrol
 * otherwise. Encode this with a top-level Selector:
 *
 * ```
 * Selector (root)
 *   ├── Sequence ("flee when low HP")
 *   │     ├── Condition: health < 30
 *   │     └── Action:    MoveAwayFromThreat
 *   ├── Sequence ("chase & attack nearby enemy")
 *   │     ├── Condition: enemy within aggro range
 *   │     └── Action:    AttackTarget
 *   └── Action ("patrol waypoint")
 *         └── MoveToNextWaypoint
 * ```
 *
 * The Selector tries branches in order. Flee wins when health is
 * low. Attack wins when flee fails and a target is close. Patrol
 * is the unconditional fallback. The example program in
 * `examples/06_ai_behavior.cpp` is exactly this tree, ticked
 * through six scenarios.
 *
 * @section tut_ai_debugging Debugging Tips
 *
 * 1. **Log status returns.** Add a decorator wrapper that logs the
 *    child's status before returning it — this is the fastest way
 *    to see which branch the tree took this tick.
 *
 * 2. **Print the blackboard on demand.** When an NPC is stuck in a
 *    weird state, dump every key and its type. Because `Blackboard`
 *    is type-erased, you need to know the types in advance — keep
 *    a dev-only registry if you find yourself debugging AI often.
 *
 * 3. **Breakpoint on `BTAction::Tick`.** Every action is a lambda,
 *    but the base class dispatches through `BTAction::Tick`. One
 *    breakpoint catches every action invocation.
 *
 * 4. **Visualize with Graphviz.** Walk the tree and emit a DOT file
 *    at server startup. Composite nodes become edges, leaves
 *    become boxes labeled with their type. A 20-node tree renders
 *    legibly and catches "why is this branch unreachable" bugs.
 *
 * 5. **Use `AIState` for log filtering.** When chasing an AI bug,
 *    grep the log by the NPC's current `AIState`. If a boss is
 *    stuck in `Fleeing` forever, you'll see it immediately.
 *
 * @section tut_ai_pitfalls Common Pitfalls
 *
 * 1. **Infinite Running loops.** A Running action that never
 *    progresses starves the rest of the Selector. Always give
 *    actions a timeout or a convergence condition and flip to
 *    Success when they reach it.
 *
 * 2. **Selector oscillation.** If two branches can both succeed
 *    and the predicate flip-flops (e.g., "enemy at 10.01m → attack,
 *    enemy at 9.99m → attack anyway"), the NPC jitters. Use
 *    hysteresis: different predicates for "start chasing" and
 *    "stop chasing".
 *
 * 3. **Mutating the tree structure at runtime.** `BTNode::Tick`
 *    is not re-entrant. Adding or removing children during a tick
 *    corrupts the composite's `currentChild_` cursor. Build the
 *    tree once; mutate the blackboard instead.
 *
 * 4. **Sharing mutable state in the tree.** Tree nodes are shared
 *    across NPCs (via `shared_ptr<BTNode>`) but the blackboard is
 *    per-entity. If a lambda captures state by reference, every
 *    NPC sees the same state — usually not what you want. Put
 *    per-entity data in the blackboard.
 *
 * 5. **Blackboard type mismatches.** `Set<int>("hp", 100)` stores
 *    an `int`; `Get<float>("hp")` returns `nullptr`. The types
 *    must match exactly. Consider a namespaced key convention
 *    like `"ai.hp"` + `"combat.hp"` when two subsystems want
 *    different types.
 *
 * 6. **Forgetting to Reset after a branch switch.** When the
 *    Selector moves from branch A to branch B, it calls `Reset()`
 *    on branch A. If A's action has side effects (e.g., an
 *    animation request), the Reset must undo them. Override
 *    `BTNode::Reset` in your action subclass when needed.
 *
 * 7. **`Running` forever because the condition never refreshes.**
 *    A Sequence that returns Running on a child stays in that
 *    child until it completes. If the parent's precondition
 *    becomes false mid-action, the Sequence still completes the
 *    action. Guard long actions with in-action bailouts.
 *
 * @section tut_ai_performance Performance Notes
 *
 * - **Tree evaluation is `O(nodes)`** in the worst case. In
 *   practice, early-exit on Success/Failure means most ticks
 *   touch only a handful of nodes. A 20-node tree evaluates in
 *   a few microseconds.
 * - **Lambda captures cost nothing at dispatch time** (virtual
 *   call + `std::function` trampoline). If you need absolute
 *   minimum overhead, subclass `BTAction` with a compile-time
 *   known function.
 * - **Shared trees save memory.** For 1,000 identical NPCs,
 *   sharing one tree costs 1× the tree allocation + 1,000×
 *   blackboards instead of 1,000× trees + 1,000× blackboards.
 * - **Throttling is the biggest win.** Default 10 Hz ticking
 *   cuts CPU cost to 20% of a per-frame implementation. For
 *   NPCs that don't need to react instantly, push the interval
 *   to 5 Hz (0.2 s) or lower.
 * - **Blackboard lookups are `O(1)`** hash operations. Cache the
 *   pointer across multiple accesses within the same lambda
 *   instead of calling `Get<T>(key)` repeatedly.
 * - **`BTAction` virtual call + `std::function` invoke**
 *   benchmarks at ~20 ns on an M2 Mac. Negligible unless you
 *   build pathologically deep trees.
 *
 * @section tut_ai_next Next Steps
 *
